{"title_page": "Karen Mossberger", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Karen Mossberger\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = [[Wayne State University]]\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Eastern Michigan University]]|[[Kent State University]]|[[University of Illinois at Chicago]]|[[University of Birmingham]]|[[Arizona State University]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = Fellow, [[National Academy of Public Administration]]\n}}\n'''Karen Mossberger''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[public policy]] and [[public administration]]. She is the Frank and June Sackton Professor of Urban Policy at [[Arizona State University]], where she is also Director of the School of Public Affairs and a Distinguished Sustainability Scholar at the Julie Ann Wrigley Global Institute of Sustainability.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spa.asu.edu/content/karen-mossberger-0 |title=Karen Mossberger |publisher=Arizona State University |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=profile/> She is an expert on the [[Diffusion of innovations#Policy|diffusion]] and implementation of policy ideas, with a particular focus on the politics of [[internet access]] in the United States.\n\n==Education and early career==\nMossberger attended [[Wayne State University]], where she earned three degrees: a BA in political science in 1991, an MA in political science in 1992, and a PhD in political science in 1996.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://sustainability.asu.edu/person/karen-mossberger/ |title=Karen Mossberger |publisher=Arizona State University |year=2017 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> During the 1992\u20131993 academic year, she was a visiting researcher at the [[University of Strathclyde]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 1996 Mossberger joined [[Eastern Michigan University]] as a lecturer, moving in 1997 to [[Kent State University]].<ref name=profile/> While a professor at Kent State University, Mossberger was involved in a visiting faculty program with [[Tver State University]], [[Volgograd State University]], and [[Voronezh State University]], and for one year she served as the Interim Director of the Center for Public Administration and Public Policy there.<ref name=profile/> In 2005 she became a professor of public policy at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]], where she later became both the Associate Dean for Faculty Affairs at the College of Urban Planning and Public Affairs and for 2 years was the Head of the Department of Public Administration.<ref name=profile/> In 2013 she became a Professor at the Arizona State University School of Public Affairs, where she was also the director for 4 years.<ref name=profile/> From 2014 to 2017, she was an honorary professor at the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn addition to her publications in peer reviewed journals and chapters in edited volumes, Mossberger has published several books. In 2000 she published ''The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones'', of which she was the sole author.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=Public Administration Review |volume=61 |date=1 January 2001 |pages=127}}</ref> The book studies how the concept of [[Urban enterprise zone|enterprise zones]] spread in the United States, using the tools of policy diffusion.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Richard C. |last=Feiock |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=The American Political Science Review |volume=95 |issue=2 |date=1 June 2001 |pages=483 |doi=}}</ref> Mossberger focuses on five states from 1981 to 1993: Indiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, New York, and Virginia.<ref name=heineman>{{cite journal |first=Robert |last=Heineman |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=Perspectives on Political Science |volume=30 |issue=2 |date=1 April 2001 |pages=106}}</ref> As part of the her analysis of the diffusion and implementation of this idea throughout several regions, Mossberger also draws conclusions about the dynamics of decision-making in a [[Federalism|federalist]] system, and under what conditions these decisions are [[Homo economicus|rational]], [[Bounded rationality|boundedly rational]], or [[Anarchy|anarchic]].<ref name=heineman/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |volume=15 |issue=4 |date=1 November 2000 |pages=71 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, together with [[Caroline Tolbert]] and William Franko, Mossberger published the book ''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity''. The book defines the notion of \"digital citizenship\" to capture the extent to which individuals are capable of regularly and effectively using technology related to the internet.<ref name=lseblog>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2013/03/19/book-review-digital-cities-the-internet-and-the-geography-of-opportunity/ |title=Book Review: Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity by Karen Mossberger et al |date=19 March 2013 |publisher=London School of Economics |last=Spicer |first=Zachary |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The authors focus on inequality in peoples' capacities to use internet technologies; Zachary Spicer, in a review of the book, wrote that they demonstrate that \"America is falling short in these areas and, as a result, information inequities are developing that could have deep and lasting impacts on the social fabric of the country.\"<ref name=lseblog/> The book also presents policy suggestions for making digital citizenship more equal.<ref name=lseblog/>\n\nMossberger's 2008 book ''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society and Participation'', coauthored with Caroline J. Tolbert and Ramona S. McNeal, was named one of the top 20 social science titles for 2008 by the [[American Library Association]].<ref name=profile/> The book was issued in a second printing in 2010. Mossberger is also the author of ''Virtual Inequality: Beyond the Digital Divide'' with Caroline J. Tolbert and Mary Stansbury (2003), and ''The Oxford Handbook of Urban Politics'' with  Susan E. Clarke and Peter John (2012).<ref name=profile/>\n\nSeveral of Mossberger's journal articles have also won best paper awards. Her 2006 article with Caroline J. Tolbert, titled \"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", was published in The ''[[Public Administration Review]]'', and was subsequently named by the journal as one of the 75 most influential articles ever published there since the journal's founding in 1940.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226011209/publicadministrationreview.org/full-list/ |title=PAR 75 Most Influential Articles |work=Public Administration Review |year=2014 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The paper was also listed as a Classic Paper by ''[[Google Scholar]]'', which recognizes \"highly-cited papers in their area of research that have stood the test of time\".<ref name=classic>{{cite web |url=https://scholar.googleblog.com/2017/06/classic-papers-articles-that-have-stood.html |title=Google Scholar Classic Papers |publisher=Google Scholar |date=14 June 2017 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Her 2005 paper \"Race, Place, and Information Technology\" received the 2005 Best Paper Award from the Public Policy Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/MEMBERSHIP/Organized-Sections/Organized-Section-Awards/Section-4 |title=Best Paper Award |publisher=American Political Science Association Public Policy Section |year=2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016,<ref name=profile/> Mossberger was named a Fellow of the American [[National Academy of Public Administration]].<ref name=fellow>{{cite web |url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20190920-professor-mary-feeney-selected-national-academy-public-administration-fellow |title=Professor Mary Feeney selected as a National Academy of Public Administration fellow |publisher=Arizona State University |date=20 September 2019 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMossberger's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-orland-bondingpoint-tl-ssw-1211-20141209-story.html |title=Orland Park residents could be rewarded for civic involvement |date=9 December 2014 |work=The Chicago Tribune |last=Zumbach |first=Lauren |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/we-used-broadband-data-we-shouldnt-have-heres-what-went-wrong/ |title=We Used Broadband Data We Shouldn't Have \u2014 Here's What Went Wrong |date=9 January 2018 |work=FiveThirtyEight |last1=Malone |first1=Clare |last2=Nguyen |first2=Mai |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vocativ]]'', and ''[[The Week]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theweek.com/articles/629994/digital-divide-much-wider-than-think |title=The digital divide is much wider than you think |date=24 June 2016 |work=The Week, from Vocativ |last=Moore |first=Tracy |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones'' (2000)\n*\"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", ''Public Administration Review'', with Caroline J. Tolbert (2006)\n*''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society and Participation'', with Caroline J. Tolbert and Ramona S. McNeal (2008)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Fellow, National Academy of Public Administration<ref name=fellow/>\n*Author of a Google Scholar Classic Paper<ref name=classic/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mossberger, Karen}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Wayne State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Kent State University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Karen Mossberger\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = [[Wayne State University]]\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Eastern Michigan University]]|[[Kent State University]]|[[University of Illinois at Chicago]]|[[University of Birmingham]]|[[Arizona State University]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = Fellow, [[National Academy of Public Administration]]\n}}\n'''Karen Mossberger''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[public policy]] and [[public administration]]. She is the Frank and June Sackton Professor of Urban Policy at [[Arizona State University]], where she is also Director of the School of Public Affairs and a Distinguished Sustainability Scholar at the Julie Ann Wrigley Global Institute of Sustainability.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spa.asu.edu/content/karen-mossberger-0 |title=Karen Mossberger |publisher=Arizona State University |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=profile/> She is an expert on the [[Diffusion of innovations#Policy|diffusion]] and implementation of policy ideas, with a particular focus on the politics of [[internet access]] in the United States.\n\n==Education and early career==\nMossberger attended [[Wayne State University]], where she earned three degrees: a BA in political science in 1991, an MA in political science in 1992, and a PhD in political science in 1996.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://sustainability.asu.edu/person/karen-mossberger/ |title=Karen Mossberger |publisher=Arizona State University |year=2017 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> During the 1992\u20131993 academic year, she was a visiting researcher at the [[University of Strathclyde]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 1996 Mossberger joined [[Eastern Michigan University]] as a lecturer, moving in 1997 to [[Kent State University]].<ref name=profile/> While a professor at Kent State University, Mossberger was involved in a visiting faculty program with [[Tver State University]], [[Volgograd State University]], and [[Voronezh State University]], and for one year she served as the Interim Director of the Center for Public Administration and Public Policy there.<ref name=profile/> In 2005 she became a professor of public policy at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]], where she later became both the Associate Dean for Faculty Affairs at the College of Urban Planning and Public Affairs and for 2 years was the Head of the Department of Public Administration.<ref name=profile/> In 2013 she became a Professor at the Arizona State University School of Public Affairs, where she was also the director for 4 years.<ref name=profile/> From 2014 to 2017, she was an honorary professor at the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn addition to her publications in peer reviewed journals and chapters in edited volumes, Mossberger has published several books. In 2000 she published ''The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones'', of which she was the sole author.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=Public Administration Review |volume=61 |date=1 January 2001 |pages=127}}</ref> The book studies how the concept of [[Urban enterprise zone|enterprise zones]] spread in the United States, using the tools of policy diffusion.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Richard C. |last=Feiock |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=The American Political Science Review |volume=95 |issue=2 |date=1 June 2001 |pages=483 |doi=}}</ref> Mossberger focuses on five states from 1981 to 1993: Indiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, New York, and Virginia.<ref name=heineman>{{cite journal |first=Robert |last=Heineman |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=Perspectives on Political Science |volume=30 |issue=2 |date=1 April 2001 |pages=106}}</ref> As part of the her analysis of the diffusion and implementation of this idea throughout several regions, Mossberger also draws conclusions about the dynamics of decision-making in a [[Federalism|federalist]] system, and under what conditions these decisions are [[Homo economicus|rational]], [[Bounded rationality|boundedly rational]], or [[Anarchy|anarchic]].<ref name=heineman/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |journal=The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones |volume=15 |issue=4 |date=1 November 2000 |pages=71 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, together with [[Caroline Tolbert]] and William Franko, Mossberger published the book ''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity''. The book defines the notion of \"digital citizenship\" to capture the extent to which individuals are capable of regularly and effectively using technology related to the internet.<ref name=lseblog>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2013/03/19/book-review-digital-cities-the-internet-and-the-geography-of-opportunity/ |title=Book Review: Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity by Karen Mossberger et al |date=19 March 2013 |publisher=London School of Economics |last=Spicer |first=Zachary |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The authors focus on inequality in peoples' capacities to use internet technologies; Zachary Spicer, in a review of the book, wrote that they demonstrate that \"America is falling short in these areas and, as a result, information inequities are developing that could have deep and lasting impacts on the social fabric of the country.\"<ref name=lseblog/> The book also presents policy suggestions for making digital citizenship more equal.<ref name=lseblog/>\n\nMossberger's 2008 book ''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society and Participation'', coauthored with Caroline J. Tolbert and Ramona S. McNeal, was named one of the top 20 social science titles for 2008 by the [[American Library Association]].<ref name=profile/> The book was issued in a second printing in 2010. Mossberger is also the author of ''Virtual Inequality: Beyond the Digital Divide'' with Caroline J. Tolbert and Mary Stansbury (2003), and ''The Oxford Handbook of Urban Politics'' with  Susan E. Clarke and Peter John (2012).<ref name=profile/>\n\nSeveral of Mossberger's journal articles have also won best paper awards. Her 2006 article with Caroline J. Tolbert, titled \"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", was published in The ''[[Public Administration Review]]'', and was subsequently named by the journal as one of the 75 most influential articles ever published there since the journal's founding in 1940.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226011209/publicadministrationreview.org/full-list/ |title=PAR 75 Most Influential Articles |work=Public Administration Review |year=2014 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The paper was also listed as a Classic Paper by ''[[Google Scholar]]'', which recognizes \"highly-cited papers in their area of research that have stood the test of time\".<ref name=classic>{{cite web |url=https://scholar.googleblog.com/2017/06/classic-papers-articles-that-have-stood.html |title=Google Scholar Classic Papers |publisher=Google Scholar |date=14 June 2017 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Her 2005 paper \"Race, Place, and Information Technology\" received the 2005 Best Paper Award from the Public Policy Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/MEMBERSHIP/Organized-Sections/Organized-Section-Awards/Section-4 |title=Best Paper Award |publisher=American Political Science Association Public Policy Section |year=2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016,<ref name=profile/> Mossberger was named a Fellow of the American [[National Academy of Public Administration]].<ref name=fellow>{{cite web |url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20190920-professor-mary-feeney-selected-national-academy-public-administration-fellow |title=Professor Mary Feeney selected as a National Academy of Public Administration fellow |publisher=Arizona State University |date=20 September 2019 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMossberger's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-orland-bondingpoint-tl-ssw-1211-20141209-story.html |title=Orland Park residents could be rewarded for civic involvement |date=9 December 2014 |work=The Chicago Tribune |last=Zumbach |first=Lauren |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/we-used-broadband-data-we-shouldnt-have-heres-what-went-wrong/ |title=We Used Broadband Data We Shouldn't Have \u2014 Here's What Went Wrong |date=9 January 2018 |work=FiveThirtyEight |last1=Malone |first1=Clare |last2=Nguyen |first2=Mai |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vocativ]]'', and ''[[The Week]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theweek.com/articles/629994/digital-divide-much-wider-than-think |title=The digital divide is much wider than you think |date=24 June 2016 |work=The Week, from Vocativ |last=Moore |first=Tracy |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''The Politics of Ideas and the Spread of Enterprise Zones'' (2000)\n*\"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", ''Public Administration Review'', with Caroline J. Tolbert (2006)\n*''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society and Participation'', with Caroline J. Tolbert and Ramona S. McNeal (2008)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Fellow, National Academy of Public Administration<ref name=fellow/>\n*Author of a Google Scholar Classic Paper<ref name=classic/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mossberger, Karen}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[[Category:Wayne State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Kent State University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karen_Mossberger"}
